ce:section.ce:para:
Ammonium is a kind of common water pollutant generally originating from industrial, agricultural and domestic wastewater. With the development of industrial and agricultural production and the improvement of people's living standards, the emission of nitrogen-containing compounds increases sharply, leading to a serious excess of ammonium content in water. Excessive ammonia nitrogen content in water causes eutrophication, which induces “red tides", leading to large numbers of deaths of fish and aquatic animals, destroying aquatic resources, polluting water quality, and ultimately affecting human life and health (Heisler et al., 2008). Ammonia nitrogen in urban rivers and lakes primarily exists in the form of ammonium ion (
NH 4 +
) with high solubility in water. Many methods including biological treatment, membrane filtration, ion exchange, chemical oxidation, adsorption, and photocatalytic oxidation can enable the removal of ammonium ion from water. Adsorption technology is considered as an efficient and universal water treatment method according to the guidelines of WHO and EPA. Ammonium ion can be effectively removed through adsorption method with low cost. The adsorbent can be recycled, which is environmentally friendly.
